 Line Following Robot

Overview  
This project builds a basic robot that can follow a black line on a light surface. 
Two IR sensors detect the line and an Arduino UNO controls the motors through an L293D driver to keep the robot on track.

 Components Used

- Arduino UNO  
- L293D motor driver IC  
- 2 IR reflectance sensors  
- Robot chassis with 2 drive wheels and 1 caster wheel  
- Li-ion battery pack (7.4 V)  
- Jumper wires  


 How It Works

- IR sensors sit at the front, close to the ground, and output LOW over the black line, HIGH on white.  
- Arduino reads both sensor values every loop.  
- Motor actions based on readings:
  - Both HIGH → move forward  
  - Left LOW, right HIGH → turn left  
  - Right LOW, left HIGH → turn right  
  - Both LOW → stop  


Wiring & Code

1. Connect IR sensor outputs to Arduino pins D2 and D3.  
2. Wire Arduino PWM pins D5/D6 and digital pins D4/D7 to the L293D inputs for the two motors.  
3. Power the L293D and motors from the Li-ion battery; share ground with the Arduino.  
4. Upload this sketch:

cpp
int leftSensor  = 2;
int rightSensor = 3;
int leftFwd     = 5;
int leftRev     = 4;
int rightFwd    = 6;
int rightRev    = 7;

void setup() {
  pinMode(leftSensor, INPUT);
  pinMode(rightSensor, INPUT);
  pinMode(leftFwd, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(leftRev, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(rightFwd, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(rightRev, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  bool L = digitalRead(leftSensor);
  bool R = digitalRead(rightSensor);

  if (L && R) {
    // forward
    digitalWrite(leftFwd, HIGH);  digitalWrite(leftRev, LOW);
    digitalWrite(rightFwd, HIGH); digitalWrite(rightRev, LOW);
  } 
  else if (!L && R) {
    // turn left
    digitalWrite(leftFwd, LOW); digitalWrite(leftRev, LOW);
    digitalWrite(rightFwd, HIGH); digitalWrite(rightRev, LOW);
  } 
  else if (L && !R) {
    // turn right
    digitalWrite(leftFwd, HIGH); digitalWrite(leftRev, LOW);
    digitalWrite(rightFwd, LOW);  digitalWrite(rightRev, LOW);
  } 
  else {
    // stop
    digitalWrite(leftFwd, LOW); digitalWrite(leftRev, LOW);
    digitalWrite(rightFwd, LOW); digitalWrite(rightRev, LOW);
  }
}


 Applications & Next Steps

- Starter project for robotics courses  
- Line-guided delivery bots  
- Experiment with PID control for smoother steering  
- Add more sensors (ultrasonic, color) for advanced following  


